    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-03T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-03T18:00:00-05:00" n="492"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d492">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 102.1/432</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-03T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 3, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2902. For <persName corresp="#p_COT1">Crosby</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_MWG1">McAdoo</persName>:</p>
                <p>No. 17. Your No. 11. My own judgment is against two councils. Concentration
                    instead of diffusion is the need of the hour, it seems to me, but am willing to
                    accept your and <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">House</persName>’s judgment whatever
                    it may be.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
